00:00:01.240 --> 00:00:05.800
This video is to give you more
examples of Fourier series.

00:00:05.800 --> 00:00:08.510
I'll start with a
function that's odd.

00:00:08.510 --> 00:00:14.080
My odd function means that
on the left side of 0,

00:00:14.080 --> 00:00:19.410
I get the negative of what I
have on the right side of 0.

00:00:19.410 --> 00:00:22.900
F at minus x is minus f of x.

00:00:22.900 --> 00:00:26.610
And it's the sine
function that's odd.

00:00:26.610 --> 00:00:31.140
The cosine function is even, and
we will have no cosines here.

00:00:31.140 --> 00:00:33.250
All the integrals
that involve cosines

00:00:33.250 --> 00:00:38.260
will tell us 0 for
the coefficients AN.

00:00:38.260 --> 00:00:41.200
What we'll get is
the B coefficients,

00:00:41.200 --> 00:00:44.340
the sine functions.

00:00:44.340 --> 00:00:49.930
So you see that I chose a simple
odd function, minus 1 or 1,

00:00:49.930 --> 00:00:55.000
which would give a square
wave if I continue it on.

00:00:55.000 --> 00:01:00.710
It will go down, up, down,
up in a square wave pattern.

00:01:00.710 --> 00:01:04.530
And I'm going to express
that as a combination

00:01:04.530 --> 00:01:07.810
of sine functions, smooth waves.

00:01:07.810 --> 00:01:10.460
And here was the
formula from last time

00:01:10.460 --> 00:01:14.780
for the coefficients
bk, except now I'm

00:01:14.780 --> 00:01:18.890
only integrating over
half, over the zero

00:01:18.890 --> 00:01:22.920
to pi part of the
interval, so I double it.

00:01:26.180 --> 00:01:29.550
So that's an odd function,
that's an odd function.

00:01:29.550 --> 00:01:32.330
When I multiply them, I
have an even function.

00:01:32.330 --> 00:01:35.180
And the integral
from minus pi to 0

00:01:35.180 --> 00:01:38.260
is just the same as the
integral from 0 to pi.

00:01:38.260 --> 00:01:44.000
So I'll do only 0 to
pi and multiply by 2.

00:01:44.000 --> 00:01:49.560
But my function on 0 to pi is 1.

00:01:49.560 --> 00:01:53.910
My nice square wave
is just plus 1 there,

00:01:53.910 --> 00:01:56.400
so I'm just
integrating sine kx dx.

00:01:56.400 --> 00:01:59.200
We can do this.

00:01:59.200 --> 00:02:02.610
It's minus cosine kx
divided by k, right?

00:02:02.610 --> 00:02:05.750
That's the integral with
the 2 over pi factor.

00:02:05.750 --> 00:02:13.660
Now I have to put
in pi and 0 and put

00:02:13.660 --> 00:02:16.890
in the limits of integration
and get the answer.

00:02:16.890 --> 00:02:18.460
So what do I get?

00:02:18.460 --> 00:02:19.670
I get 2 over pi.

00:02:26.610 --> 00:02:33.450
For k equal 1, I think
I get-- so k is 1,

00:02:33.450 --> 00:02:38.620
the denominator will be 1, and
I think the numerator is 2.

00:02:38.620 --> 00:02:42.740
Yes, when k is 0, I get yeah.

00:02:42.740 --> 00:02:45.380
When k is 1, I get 2.

00:02:45.380 --> 00:02:49.960
When k is 2, so
this is 4 over pi,

00:02:49.960 --> 00:02:52.900
I figured out as the
first coefficient.

00:02:52.900 --> 00:02:56.960
The coefficient b1 is 4 over pi.

00:02:56.960 --> 00:03:02.220
The coefficient b2, now if I
take k equal to 2, I have a 2

00:03:02.220 --> 00:03:03.520
down below.

00:03:03.520 --> 00:03:09.380
But above, I have a 0
because the cosine of 2 pi

00:03:09.380 --> 00:03:12.810
is the same as the cosine of 0.

00:03:12.810 --> 00:03:17.370
When I subtract I get
nothing, so that's 0.

00:03:17.370 --> 00:03:20.420
Now I go to k equals 3.

00:03:20.420 --> 00:03:23.790
So the k equals 3
will come down here.

00:03:23.790 --> 00:03:30.000
And now when k is 3, it turns
out I get-- they don't cancel,

00:03:30.000 --> 00:03:31.140
they reinforce.

00:03:31.140 --> 00:03:32.870
I get another 2.

00:03:32.870 --> 00:03:34.400
Good if you do these.

00:03:34.400 --> 00:03:37.220
And when k is 4,
I get a 0 again.

00:03:37.220 --> 00:03:38.210
You see the pattern?

00:03:42.380 --> 00:03:50.030
The pattern for the integrals
is the k is going 1, 2, 3, 4, 5.

00:03:50.030 --> 00:03:54.900
This part gives me a 2 or
a 0 or a 2 or a 0 in order.

00:03:54.900 --> 00:03:57.530
If you check that,
you'll get it.

00:03:57.530 --> 00:04:02.220
So I see that now for this
function, which is better

00:04:02.220 --> 00:04:03.830
than the delta function also.

00:04:03.830 --> 00:04:05.600
It's not very smooth.

00:04:05.600 --> 00:04:07.000
It has jumps.

00:04:07.000 --> 00:04:10.110
It's a jump function,
a step function.

00:04:10.110 --> 00:04:14.319
I see some decay,
some slow decay,

00:04:14.319 --> 00:04:15.485
in the Fourier coefficients.

00:04:18.959 --> 00:04:24.540
This factor k is growing so
the numbers are going to 0,

00:04:24.540 --> 00:04:26.110
but not very fast.

00:04:26.110 --> 00:04:27.460
Not very fast.

00:04:27.460 --> 00:04:31.580
Because my function
is not very smooth.

00:04:31.580 --> 00:04:37.520
So now you see-- so if
I use those numbers,

00:04:37.520 --> 00:04:45.360
I'm saying that the square wave,
this function, the minus 1 to 1

00:04:45.360 --> 00:04:49.950
function, is equal
to, let's see.

00:04:49.950 --> 00:04:57.000
I might as well take
that 4 over pi times 1.

00:04:57.000 --> 00:05:08.890
So that's 1 sine x, 0, sine 2x's
then 4 over pi sine 3x's, but

00:05:08.890 --> 00:05:14.750
with this guy there's
a 3, 0 sine 4x's,

00:05:14.750 --> 00:05:23.840
sine 5x comes in
over 5, and so on.

00:05:23.840 --> 00:05:26.480
That's a kind of nice example.

00:05:26.480 --> 00:05:31.930
It turns out that we have
just the odd frequencies 1, 3,

00:05:31.930 --> 00:05:38.380
5 in the square wave and
they're multiplied by 4 over pi

00:05:38.380 --> 00:05:43.230
and they're divided by the
frequency, so that's the decay.

00:05:43.230 --> 00:05:46.020
There is an odd function.

00:05:46.020 --> 00:05:49.180
Why don't I integrate
that function?

00:05:49.180 --> 00:05:51.140
If I want to get
an even function

00:05:51.140 --> 00:05:53.740
to show you an even
example, I'll just

00:05:53.740 --> 00:05:55.910
integrate that square wave.

00:05:55.910 --> 00:05:58.840
When I integrate it square
wave, it'll be even.

00:05:58.840 --> 00:06:03.025
Maybe I'll start the integral
at 0, then it goes up at 1.

00:06:05.960 --> 00:06:12.300
And here the integral is
negative, so it's coming down.

00:06:12.300 --> 00:06:20.910
So you see it's a-- what am I
going to call this function?

00:06:20.910 --> 00:06:23.990
Sort of a repeating
ramp function.

00:06:23.990 --> 00:06:27.410
It's a ramp down and then
up, down and then up.

00:06:27.410 --> 00:06:31.770
But of course from minus pi to
pi, that's where I'm looking.

00:06:31.770 --> 00:06:35.360
I'm looking between
minus pi and pi.

00:06:35.360 --> 00:06:39.770
And I see that function is even.

00:06:39.770 --> 00:06:41.320
And what does even mean?

00:06:41.320 --> 00:06:45.780
That means that my
function at minus--

00:06:45.780 --> 00:06:48.745
there is minus x-- is the
same as the value at x.

00:06:51.920 --> 00:06:56.420
And what that means for a
Fourier series is cosine.

00:06:56.420 --> 00:06:59.370
Even functions only
have cosine terms.

00:06:59.370 --> 00:07:01.940
And of course, since
I've just integrated,

00:07:01.940 --> 00:07:04.570
I might as well just
integrate that series.

00:07:04.570 --> 00:07:09.340
So this is this ramp, this
repeating ramp function,

00:07:09.340 --> 00:07:13.150
is going to be 4 over pi.

00:07:13.150 --> 00:07:15.760
I could figure out the
cosine coefficients,

00:07:15.760 --> 00:07:18.700
the a's, patiently.

00:07:18.700 --> 00:07:21.530
But why should I do that
when I can just integrate?

00:07:24.890 --> 00:07:28.260
So the integral of
sine x will be minus

00:07:28.260 --> 00:07:31.590
is the integral of
sine x, is minus cosine

00:07:31.590 --> 00:07:38.590
x, so I'll put the minus
there, cosine x over 1 I guess.

00:07:38.590 --> 00:07:40.130
Now what's the integral of this?

00:07:40.130 --> 00:07:46.510
The integral of sine 3x
is a cosine 3x over 3.

00:07:46.510 --> 00:07:48.750
And there's another
3 and there's

00:07:48.750 --> 00:07:51.560
a minus sign, which I've got.

00:07:51.560 --> 00:07:57.540
So I think it's cosine
of 3x over 3 squared,

00:07:57.540 --> 00:08:00.580
because I have one 3
there and I get another 3

00:08:00.580 --> 00:08:01.810
from the integration.

00:08:01.810 --> 00:08:05.540
And similarly here,
when I integrate sine 5x

00:08:05.540 --> 00:08:09.930
I get cos 5x with a 5.

00:08:09.930 --> 00:08:13.570
And then I already had
one 5, so 5 squared.

00:08:13.570 --> 00:08:16.260
So there you go.

