00:09:07.550 --> 00:09:09.870
what do you see now?

00:09:09.870 --> 00:09:12.660
That's the other example
I wanted you to see.

00:09:12.660 --> 00:09:15.180
You see a faster drop off.

00:09:15.180 --> 00:09:20.630
1, 9, 25, 49, whatever.

00:09:20.630 --> 00:09:24.820
It's dropping off
with k squared.

00:09:24.820 --> 00:09:28.930
And the reason it drops
off faster than this one

00:09:28.930 --> 00:09:32.820
is that it's smoother.

00:09:32.820 --> 00:09:35.210
This function has corners.

00:09:35.210 --> 00:09:37.890
This function has jumps.

00:09:37.890 --> 00:09:43.650
So a jump is one level
more rough, more word

00:09:43.650 --> 00:09:47.340
noisy than a ramp function.

00:09:47.340 --> 00:09:50.670
The smoother function
has faster decay.

00:09:50.670 --> 00:09:53.060
Smooth-- let me
write those words--

00:09:53.060 --> 00:10:04.680
smooth function connects
with faster decay.

00:10:04.680 --> 00:10:08.160
Faster drop off of the
Fourier coefficient.

00:10:08.160 --> 00:10:11.100
It means that the Fourier
series is much more useful.

00:10:11.100 --> 00:10:14.900
Fourier series is really
terrific for functions

00:10:14.900 --> 00:10:20.760
that are smooth because then you
only need to keep a few terms.

00:10:20.760 --> 00:10:26.550
For functions that have
jumps or delta functions,

00:10:26.550 --> 00:10:28.880
you have to keep
many, many terms

00:10:28.880 --> 00:10:31.380
and the Fourier
series calculation

00:10:31.380 --> 00:10:33.620
is much more difficult.

00:10:33.620 --> 00:10:38.530
So that's the second example.

