00:10:47.010 --> 00:10:49.950
end with just two basic rules.

00:10:49.950 --> 00:10:53.340
Two basic rules.

00:10:53.340 --> 00:10:57.940
So the rule for derivatives.

00:11:02.460 --> 00:11:05.380
What's the Fourier
series of df dx?

00:11:09.180 --> 00:11:13.005
And the second will
be the rule for shift.

00:11:16.650 --> 00:11:23.130
What's the Fourier series
for f of x minus a shift?

00:11:23.130 --> 00:11:26.940
You know that when I change
x to x minus d, all that does

00:11:26.940 --> 00:11:30.550
is shift the graph
by a distance d.

00:11:30.550 --> 00:11:34.250
That should do something nice
to its Fourier coefficient.

00:11:34.250 --> 00:11:37.230
So I'm starting with--
oh, I haven't given you

00:11:37.230 --> 00:11:40.140
any practice with
a complex case.

00:11:40.140 --> 00:11:41.690
This would be a good time.

00:11:41.690 --> 00:11:52.390
Suppose start is f of
x equals the sum of ck,

00:11:52.390 --> 00:11:58.140
a complex coefficient e to the
ikx, the complex exponential.

00:11:58.140 --> 00:12:01.860
And you'll remember that
sum went from minus infinity

00:12:01.860 --> 00:12:02.360
to infinity.

00:12:06.330 --> 00:12:08.260
So I have a Fourier series.

00:12:08.260 --> 00:12:12.510
I'm imagining I know the
coefficients and I want to say,

00:12:12.510 --> 00:12:14.490
what happens if I
take the derivative?

00:12:14.490 --> 00:12:16.740
Well, just take the derivative.

00:12:16.740 --> 00:12:26.640
You'll have a sum of the
derivative brings down

00:12:26.640 --> 00:12:30.000
a factor ik.

00:12:30.000 --> 00:12:31.860
So that's the rule.

00:12:31.860 --> 00:12:33.500
Simple, but important.

00:12:33.500 --> 00:12:37.390
That's why Fourier series
is so great because you

00:12:37.390 --> 00:12:40.450
have orthogonality and then
you have this simple rule

00:12:40.450 --> 00:12:43.340
with derivatives.

00:12:43.340 --> 00:12:46.910
it just brings a factor
ik so the derivative

00:12:46.910 --> 00:12:52.890
make sure function noisier and
you have larger coefficients.

00:12:52.890 --> 00:12:55.730
And if I do f of
x minus d, so I'll

00:12:55.730 --> 00:13:04.120
change x to x minus d, so I'll
see the sum of ck e to the ikx,

00:13:04.120 --> 00:13:08.950
e to the minus ikd, right?

00:13:08.950 --> 00:13:13.290
I've put in x minus
d instead of x.

00:13:13.290 --> 00:13:17.690
And here I see that the Fourier
coefficient for a shifted

00:13:17.690 --> 00:13:23.636
function-- so the ck was a
Fourier coefficient for f.

00:13:23.636 --> 00:13:28.070
When I shift f, it
multiplies that coefficient

00:13:28.070 --> 00:13:31.650
by a phase change.

00:13:31.650 --> 00:13:34.310
The magnitude stayed
the same because that's

00:13:34.310 --> 00:13:39.730
a number-- everybody recognizes
that as a number of magnitude 1

00:13:39.730 --> 00:13:43.700
and just has a phase shift.

00:13:43.700 --> 00:13:46.050
Those are two would
rules that show

00:13:46.050 --> 00:13:51.220
why you can use Fourier series
in differential equations

00:13:51.220 --> 00:13:54.400
and in difference equations.

00:13:54.400 --> 00:13:56.120
